wa: First known case of COVID-19 in U.S.

lifeCare: Staff notice an outbreak of respiratory illness.
Resident's son becomes sick with COVID-19 after visiting nursing home.

First resident taken to the hospital who later tests positive for COVID-19.

At the time, Life Care has 120 residents, 180 employees.
74-year-old woman is the first resident who tests positive for COVID-19 and dies on March 2.
audio: 55 year-old man taken to Harborview Medical Center. He died Feb. 26 but was not linked to COVID-19 until later.
speaker: A 55-year-old resident goes to Harborview Medical Center later that day. He died Feb. 26 but was not linked to COVID-19 until later.

lifeCare:
Mardi Gras party at Life Care.

An 86-year-old resident dies after moving to another facility; her death is later linked to COVID-19.
speaker: 92-year-old female Pneumonia, difficulty breathing

lifeCare: Life Care Center notifies Public Health - Seattle & King County of an increase in respiratory illness, but has no details about the illness or number of people affected.
speaker: A Life Care employee calls 911 to report a 74-year-old resident had difficulty breathing.
speaker2: A Life Care employees calls 911 to report a resident in her 80s has a fever and difficulty breathing.
wa: The CDC expands testing critieria - previously focused on international travel - to people with unexplained severe symptoms not linked to the flu. Evergreen hospital alerts public health officials that multiple patients have come from Life Care Center, including one with symptoms suspected to be COVID-19.

Public Health learns 20 residents are ill and tested negative for the flu. Another hospital reports a Life Care-related case. Shoreline lab begins testing. Preliminary test results come back positive for four cases, including two Life Care residents. County health officials contact the CDC and state officials.

lifeCare: A handful of CDC staff arrive. Public Health announce the first two COVID-19: A resident in her 70s and employee in her 40s. A man in his 70s dies at EvergreenHealth; his death is announced the next day.
audio: 79-year-old woman, fever, low oxygen, difficulty breathing.
speaker: 79-year-old female Fever, low oxygen, difficulty breathing

lifeCare: Public Health announces new cases linked to Life Care, bringing the total to six, including one death.
speaker: 63-year-old male Difficulty breathing, turning blue

audio: 90-year-old woman, drowsy, hypoxic (difficulty breathing, low oxygen).
speaker: 90-year-old female Drowsy, hypoxic (difficulty breathing, low oxygen)
speaker2: 74-year-old male Shortness of breath, low oxygen
speaker3: 90-year-old female Difficulty breathing, low oxygen, high heart rate

wa: CDC lifts all restrictions on who can get tested

lifeCare: No residents still at Life Care had been tested, according to Public Health Seattle & King County.
wa: Health officer Jeff Duchin from Public Health - Seattle & King County says the county is working to get everyone at Life Care tested. “They likely have been infected or are at high risk for infection.”

lifeCare: Families of Life Care residents hold a news conference to vent frustrations over communication, lack of testing.

wa: Inslee agrees to set up incident-command structure for nursing homes that experience outbreaks federal natural-disaster team arrives.

lifeCare:
Life Care holds its first press conference, indicating the number of deaths and illnesses could be higher than originally thought. A spokesman said not all residents had been tested.

Life Care obtains enough kits to test all residents that night.
wa: Washington state Department of Social and Health Services and U.S. Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services enter Life Care to begin investigation.

lifeCare: University of Washington collects samples from remaining symptomatic employees in the nursing home parking lot.
43 of 120 residents remain at Life Care and 30 have tested positive; 102 of 180 employees have shown symptoms (46 positive)
